On Tuesday, a law restricting the acquisition of substances suitable for the manufacture of explosives will enter into force in Finland.
In future, private individuals will have to apply for a licence from the National Police Board to purchase or possess substances or mixtures that could be used as a precursor for explosives.
Such substances include hydrogen peroxide, nitromethane, nitric acid, potassium chlorate, potassium chlorate, sodium chlorate and sodium perchlorate and mixtures containing them, if the specified concentration values are exceeded.
Hydrogen peroxide can be found, for example, in cleaning products and detergents, but the concentrations do not usually exceed the limit values.
