Ovarian cancer is more common in sparsely populated areas due to late diagnosis and difficult access to treatment
Angelina Jolie and her brother James have posted a video as a tribute to their mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
In Australia, women living in rural areas have a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than those living in cities.
The researchers reviewed the medical records of more than 1100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005 and found that only 35 per cent of women lived more than five years after diagnosis.
Principal investigator Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Medical Research Institute confirms that women living in sparsely populated and remote areas were 20 percent more likely to die during the study than women living in urban areas.
SMALL STUDY: New drugs may slow down lung and ovarian cancer
The researchers reviewed the women's health history over a seven-year period.
According to Dr. Susan Jordan, the woman's age at the time of diagnosis, the type of ovarian cancer, previous illnesses and socioeconomic status also affected the chances of survival.
Older women and when the cancer was more widespread at the time of diagnosis had the lowest probability of survival.
Women living in sparsely populated and remote areas were 20% more likely to die during the study than women living in urban areas.
The study did not seek to determine why women living outside cities are less likely to survive ovarian cancer, but Jordan sees delayed diagnosis and difficult access to treatment as possible causes.
"Gynecological oncology specialists treat this disease best, and their practices are mostly located in large cities," Jordan says.
Although telemedicine is becoming more common and distance is becoming less important, the researcher suggests increasing the mobility of doctors so that specialists can treat patients closer to home, as well as programmes to support patients being treated far from home.
According to Dr. Jordan's research, women with ovarian cancer have poor long-term survival rates regardless of geographic location, highlighting the need for better treatment and better cancer prevention programs.
The study, funded by the Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer Cancer charity, is published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, Elisha TNeave, a 33-year-old mother living on the Gold Coast, was diagnosed with malignant ovarian cancer.
