Genetic abnormality is often misdiagnosed
For years, a British woman feared death due to a misdiagnosis.
For most of her youth, Karin Rodgers thought she only had a few years left to live because she had been diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, he suffered from Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease (CMT). It means a group of hereditary diseases that damage the nerves outside the brain and spine.
According to charity CMT UK, misdiagnosis is a common problem in CMT cases because so little is known about them.
It is estimated that around 23,000 people in the UK suffer from CMT, which causes motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, awkward walking and curled toes.
The disease can also cause numbness or pain, and is incurable and progressive, which means that symptoms worsen over time.
When Rodgers was 13, he thought he had Friedreich's ataxia (FA), which has a very poor survival rate.
Rodgers believed he would be confined to a wheelchair before he turned 18 and die before he reached the age of 30.
Today, the 51-year-old mother of two says, "As a child, I knew I couldn't do the same things as others.
I fell every day and it took me longer than everyone else.
I was never able to roller skate or skateboard with other kids, and I was bullied at school because I walked and ran differently from others.
When Rodgers was 13, he underwent several Achilles tendon surgeries to straighten his legs. During the surgeries, after the doctor left the room, he quickly glanced at his examination papers that said he had FA.
"I felt guilty because I was so curious, so I didn't tell anyone, but when I got home, I checked the information about the illness in the library and wrote to the FA Association," she says.
When I received information from them, I was shocked and in a state of panic.
I thought I would be confined to a wheelchair by the age of 18 and die before I was 25, and in the meantime I would slowly lose my full functionality.
I went through this on my own and planned my own funeral.
Rodgers says that by the age of 17, he found that his gait had not deteriorated as much as he had thought and asked his doctor about this.
The doctor just hugged me and said, "girl baby, I don't think you have this disease because otherwise you would already be in a wheelchair".
I think you're suffering from a much less dangerous disease.
Based on some genetic tests, he was diagnosed with CMT.
"When they explained to me what CMT was, I thought I put it off," she says.
Charity CMT UK – organises CMT Month to draw attention to the condition.
