A smart way to save on textbooks
The cost of college books in America exceeds $1,000 for many students, so Matt Schroeder, who will soon be entering his second year of college, came up with a smart way to save costs.
He developed a system in which students in later years borrow their books for a nominal fee instead of selling them right away.
"My math book would normally have cost $180; I paid $10 for the whole semester and a hearty sandwich," says Schroeder, a 19-year-old student at Covenant College in Georgia.
Schroeder says his books from last semester would normally have cost $430.
Instead, he spent $120 on them.
According to the University Board of Trustees, the average student spends more than $1,200 a year on textbooks and school supplies, but there are many ways for students to reduce these costs.
Students are increasingly choosing to use online stores and creative approaches such as Schroeder's idea.
More and more students are renting textbooks, allowing them to use the book throughout the semester and paying significantly less for it than students who buy it.
According to Neebo Inc, a company that operates more than 250 campus bookstores, textbook rentals have doubled since 2011.
Statistics on the industry reveal that about a quarter of the books in university bookstores this spring were rental books, says Trevor Meyer, chairman of Neebo.
According to the National Association of College Stores, less than half of all books are purchased from campus bookstores.
Here are the simplest ways to save money.
Shopping
In online stores, you can get a new book for only a third of the price it would cost in a campus bookstore.
The recommended retail price for the ninth edition of "Calculus" by Ron Larson, Bruce Edwards and Robert Hostetler is nearly $290, but the book Chegg.com available online is $239.99.
Used Buy
Used books are a good option if the reader is not distracted by the notes and worn appearance of others.
For example, the book "Calculus" can be obtained second-hand from Chegg.com for $93.49.
Brigham Young University's final-year student Matt Casaday, 25, says he bought the book "Strategic Media Decisions: Understanding The Business End Of The Advertising Business" second-hand on Amazon.com for just $0.42.
When new, the book would have cost $48.
Ingrid Bracey, director of Amherst's College Without Walls at the University of Massachusetts, and other academics recommend that students ask their professors if previous editions can be used in the course.
Sometimes the reforms of the new edition are not relevant to teaching.
In this case, the old edition can only be found for a fraction of the price that should be paid for the new one.
In addition to Chegg and Amazon bookstores, eBay Inc's Half.com is a popular place to buy used books.
Renting
You should consider renting textbooks if you take good care of them, remember to return them and don't need them after completing the course.
By renting, you can save more than 80 percent of the price of a new book.
For example, renting a "Calculus" book for an entire semester costs about $20.
Review the rental company's rules, including fees for notes, highlighter use, and wear.
Renter, beware: if you forget to return a book, the late fee may be higher than the purchase price of the book.
E-books
Purchasing e-books instead of regular paper ones may also be an option.
Sometimes these books are rented, in which case the holder is paid for the right to use the e-book, such as Amazon.com, Chegg, or Barnes & Noble Inc. bookstores.
At Chegg, you can get "Calculus" as an eBook for six months for about $61.
According to Bracey, many literature students save the most because many classics today can be downloaded for free, while books in the field of science and technology can be very expensive.
It's worth comparing different sellers, whichever option you choose.
Joe Gault, 29, who will soon start at Pepperdine Law School, recommends using the book ISBN to find out the price to make sure you're looking for the right book.
Before ordering online, make sure the book is in stock, Gault says.
He himself learned this the hard way.
The delivery of the book he had bought was on hold for four weeks, and he eventually had to buy the book at full price from the university bookstore.
